iOpenSSL provides experimental support for TLS 1.3 in its latest beta		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iversion, including a series of performance and security optimizations.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe latest nginx 1.13 series has also added relevant options for TLS		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1.3.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iHowever, since TLS 1.3 is still in draft status, there are some		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ichallenges to overcome when using it now:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. TLS 1.3 currently has three draft versions (18, 19, 20) implemented		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   by OpenSSL and others, but they are mutually incompatible, and no		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   SSL library combines all three.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i2. Browsers like Chrome and Firefox widely use draft version 18, but		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   this version of OpenSSL doesn't support TLS extensions, which are		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   required for Certificate Transparency.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i3. Although the latest		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   nginx-ct		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   plugin adds Certificate Transparency support for TLS 1.3, due to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   issue #2, it fails to compile when used with OpenSSL draft 18.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   Therefore, you must revert to version 1.3.2 from the nginx-ct		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   project		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   releases		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   , which doesn't support TLS 1.3.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
