i## Detecting TLS version in FastCGI		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSince SSL connections aren't typically established directly with		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ibackend services like PHP FastCGI, these backends can't detect the TLS		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iversion or encryption method. However, nginx can obtain this		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iinformation and store it as variables. By simply modifying the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iconfiguration, this information can be passed to FastCGI backends.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iOpen the `fastcgi_params` file in your nginx configuration directory		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iand add two lines:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  fastcgi_param  SSL_CIPHER         $ssl_cipher;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  fastcgi_param  SSL_PROTOCOL       $ssl_protocol;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThen reload the nginx configuration. For PHP, this information can be		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iaccessed via `$_SERVER['SSL_CIPHER']` and similar methods.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
